WEBVTT

00:01.887 --> 00:05.721
NARRATOR: In 1972, a crack commando unit
was sent to prison by a military court...

00:05.807 --> 00:07.320
for a crime they didn't commit.

00:07.407 --> 00:10.240
These men promptly escaped
from a maximum security stockade...

00:10.327 --> 00:11.806
to the Los Angeles underground.

00:11.887 --> 00:15.402
Today, still wanted by the government,
they survive as soldiers of fortune.

00:15.487 --> 00:17.842
If you have a problem,
if no one else can help...

00:17.927 --> 00:21.317
and if you can find them,
maybe you can hire the A-Team.

00:23.967 --> 00:25.366
[Theme music]

00:27.000 --> 00:33.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:39.767 --> 01:42.076
[Light, flute-based instrumental music]

01:58.927 --> 02:00.440
[Boat chugging]

02:05.567 --> 02:07.717
CAL: Okay, Shana, shut her down.

02:08.806 --> 02:10.525
DOUG: I'll get the camera and the charts.

02:10.607 --> 02:14.282
CAL: Move it. I want to make the Maritime
Office and the Fish and Game by 5:00.

02:14.367 --> 02:15.846
Those pictures we took of Garber...

02:15.927 --> 02:18.361
catching lobster
outside the restricted area...

02:18.447 --> 02:21.007
CAL: should open somebody's eyes.
DOUG: Yeah.

02:23.007 --> 02:24.042
Dad.

02:33.887 --> 02:37.277
Garber, you're on my dock.
It's private property. Get off!

02:37.367 --> 02:40.677
I don't like it when people
try to sabotage my boats, Mayer.

02:40.767 --> 02:44.521
Sabotage? We didn't come within 500 yards.

02:44.927 --> 02:47.964
We took pictures,
we checked the lobster beds underneath.

02:48.047 --> 02:49.560
Now, we've been watching you.

02:49.647 --> 02:52.764
We have evidence to prove
you're destroying the future of this bay.

02:52.847 --> 02:54.678
But we wouldn't touch your boats.

02:54.767 --> 02:57.122
When we stop you, Garber,
we're gonna do it legal.

02:57.207 --> 02:59.198
You got a big mouth, kid.

02:59.767 --> 03:01.485
But I'll give you a break.

03:01.807 --> 03:04.605
I'll let you stay in business,
provided you accept my deal.

03:04.687 --> 03:08.282
Give you half of the profits from our catch
like everyone else around here?

03:08.367 --> 03:09.880
Pay protection?

03:10.607 --> 03:14.839
Listen, Garber, we work hard for our money,
so why don't you take a walk?

03:16.647 --> 03:18.365
[Dramatic instrumental music]

03:18.447 --> 03:19.482
No!

03:20.367 --> 03:21.561
[Grunts]

03:22.847 --> 03:23.962
SHANA: Dad.

03:25.887 --> 03:27.081
[Groans]

03:30.687 --> 03:33.406
Your dad and your brother
are stupid men, Shana.

03:33.727 --> 03:35.683
Now, you better talk some sense into them...

03:35.767 --> 03:39.043
before somebody finds them washed up
on one of these beaches down here.

03:39.127 --> 03:40.560
I run this town.

03:41.767 --> 03:44.918
The sooner they accept that,
the longer they're gonna live.

03:45.007 --> 03:46.281
[Sighs loudly]

03:46.487 --> 03:48.603
[Sinister instrumental music]

03:48.687 --> 03:49.961
Why don't we...

03:50.047 --> 03:52.686
see if we can help these folks out
with their boat, boys.

03:52.767 --> 03:55.042
See it's running all right. Okay?

03:55.967 --> 03:57.878
[Soft instrumental music]

03:58.767 --> 04:00.405
[Glass shattering]

04:04.327 --> 04:06.283
[Tense instrumental music]

04:16.087 --> 04:17.315
[Hissing]

04:31.967 --> 04:33.559
[Tyres screeching]

04:45.247 --> 04:48.080
B.A.: Hey, be careful with my foot.
It ain't no packing crate.

04:48.167 --> 04:49.566
Don't you just love it?

04:49.647 --> 04:51.797
FACE: We have six near misses
with Col. Decker...

04:51.887 --> 04:54.640
avoid half his platoon
back there on that bridge...

04:54.727 --> 04:57.036
and then you go and step on a rusty nail.

04:57.127 --> 04:58.719
HANNIBAL: Some guys got all the luck.

04:58.807 --> 05:01.879
That nail sure didn't.
He was screaming in pain under your foot.

05:01.967 --> 05:03.798
All scrunched up on that board like that.

05:03.887 --> 05:06.526
Poor little fellow probably had a family
and everything.

05:06.607 --> 05:08.723
Don't worry, B.A.,
we'll take care of everything.

05:08.807 --> 05:12.163
We'll get you a tetanus shot and leave
before Decker knows where we are.

05:12.247 --> 05:14.556
Face, handle the red tape.
I want to stick out here.

05:14.647 --> 05:16.922
FACE: My pleasure.
B.A.: That's easy for you to say.

05:17.007 --> 05:18.486
[Face chuckling]

05:20.927 --> 05:22.246
[Thudding]

05:28.927 --> 05:31.885
Murdock, why are you eating
a sandwich that's frozen?

05:32.767 --> 05:34.644
I have to. I'm allergic to microwaves.

05:34.727 --> 05:37.446
It releases space hamsters
into my blood stream.

05:39.607 --> 05:42.041
Have you gotten any word
on my father and brother yet?

05:42.127 --> 05:45.244
Excuse me. How's our friend doing?
Cheery fellow with the cut foot.

05:45.327 --> 05:47.636
I'm afraid that your father's
in critical condition.

05:47.727 --> 05:49.683
The doctor's gonna suggest
that we move him...

05:49.767 --> 05:51.359
to Los Angeles Memorial Hospital.

05:51.447 --> 05:54.564
He'll get better treatment there.
We don't have the equipment here.

05:54.647 --> 05:55.796
Los Angeles?

05:55.887 --> 05:59.038
NURSE: With all his internal injuries,
he'll have a better chance there.

05:59.127 --> 06:01.595
We'll be releasing your brother
in just a little while.

06:01.687 --> 06:04.565
He's pretty banged up,
but he's gonna be all right.

06:04.687 --> 06:05.915
[Sighs] Thanks.

06:08.927 --> 06:11.395
NURSE: What'd you say
your friend's name was again, please?

06:11.487 --> 06:14.047
Lothar Quint. With a "Q."

06:14.687 --> 06:16.962
You've probably seen him
on daytime soap operas.

06:17.047 --> 06:19.356
Had a big guest role
on Search for Tomorrow.

06:19.447 --> 06:21.836
Played a pro quarterback
who turned psychic.

06:21.927 --> 06:23.758
Yeah, he was just marvellous.

06:24.127 --> 06:25.242
Lothar?

06:25.367 --> 06:26.880
[Murmuring agreement]

06:28.887 --> 06:30.036
[Door shuts]

06:30.127 --> 06:32.595
Cool it, gang. The sheriff just pulled up.

06:43.087 --> 06:45.521
What's going on? Somebody get hurt?

06:45.807 --> 06:49.482
Yeah, Garber and his animals
came out to our boat and tore it all up.

06:49.567 --> 06:52.161
Beat up my dad real bad. Doug, too.

06:52.687 --> 06:54.882
You sure your dad didn't push him to it?

06:54.967 --> 06:56.605
CaI can be awfuI hard to take.

06:56.687 --> 06:59.963
Your whole family's been stirring things up
around here for some time.

07:00.047 --> 07:03.039
Should have known better
than to come to you for help.

07:03.327 --> 07:05.238
You're afraid of Garber.

07:06.127 --> 07:09.597
But even more, you're afraid
that he's gonna take away all that money...

07:09.687 --> 07:11.996
he's waving in front of your face.

07:13.927 --> 07:14.996
[Newman sighs]

07:15.087 --> 07:16.964
Give my best to Doug and Cal.

07:18.247 --> 07:20.681
Nice quiet little seaside town, huh?

07:20.767 --> 07:22.200
[Door closes]

07:28.807 --> 07:31.480
MURDOCK: Hey, B.A., how you feeling, guy?
Lockjaw set in yet?

07:31.567 --> 07:34.206
Get out of here, sucker!
At least I don't have lock-brain!

07:34.287 --> 07:38.439
And don't forget, I still got two feet,
so kicking you ain't gonna be no problem.

07:41.247 --> 07:42.885
Could I help you, ma'am?

07:44.007 --> 07:46.202
I guess this just isn't my day.

07:46.927 --> 07:48.406
[Coin clinking]

07:48.607 --> 07:52.441
You know, we couldn't help but overhear,
and if you...

07:53.727 --> 07:56.400
feel like blowing off a little steam...

07:56.887 --> 07:58.684
we'd be glad to listen.

08:04.887 --> 08:06.923
Leader to Hook. Come in, Colonel.

08:07.647 --> 08:08.682
This is Decker. Over.

08:09.167 --> 08:12.079
No dice at Seaside Memorial
or Coastline Hospital, sir.

08:13.047 --> 08:15.436
That means they got to be
at Lobster Bay Hospital.

08:15.527 --> 08:17.597
It's the only other one in the area.

08:17.687 --> 08:20.838
And that blood we found
didn't come from their flat tyre.

08:21.527 --> 08:23.245
Rendezvous there, ASAP.

08:23.887 --> 08:27.277
You obey the speed signs, Captain,
and I'll bust you down to your socks.

08:27.687 --> 08:29.006
We're moving out now.

08:29.087 --> 08:30.236
Let's hit it.

08:30.767 --> 08:32.678
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

08:32.767 --> 08:34.563
[Police sirens blaring]

08:39.927 --> 08:41.519
[Tyres screeching]

08:50.487 --> 08:53.206
Yeah. And as soon as Garber's done
ripping off this place...

08:53.287 --> 08:56.040
he'll just slither up the coast
in his fancy boats...

08:56.127 --> 08:59.756
and wreck someplace else
where people have fished for a generation.

09:00.247 --> 09:01.760
All he cares about is profits.

09:01.847 --> 09:03.724
And once he's wiped out the lobster beds...

09:03.807 --> 09:06.605
there's no way they'll be able
to replenish themselves, right?

09:06.687 --> 09:07.756
That's right.

09:07.847 --> 09:09.883
But I thought nature
always replenished itself.

09:09.967 --> 09:13.243
It does. I mean, look at me.
A few years ago, I was a basket case.

09:13.327 --> 09:15.636
It depends on how much
you take from nature, Amy.

09:15.727 --> 09:16.955
And how much you leave behind.

09:17.047 --> 09:18.765
DOUG: Garber isn't gonna leave anything.

09:18.847 --> 09:21.839
If it was just he and his men
there couldn't be too much damage.

09:21.927 --> 09:24.805
Yeah, but he makes the fishermen
give him half their profits.

09:24.887 --> 09:27.799
So they have to fish twice as much
just to stay alive.

09:27.887 --> 09:29.525
Straight extortion.

09:30.047 --> 09:33.676
If the working people don't pay Garber,
he breaks their arms.

09:33.927 --> 09:37.363
I wouldn't be surprised if next time
he tries to kill us.

09:38.007 --> 09:41.124
I'm not so sure
he hasn't already killed our father.

09:43.367 --> 09:45.562
Maybe he's gonna beat us this time after all.

09:45.647 --> 09:47.080
I don't know.

09:51.727 --> 09:53.240
I think you need some help.

09:53.327 --> 09:54.919
Are you volunteering?

09:55.007 --> 09:56.076
Yes, ma'am.

09:56.207 --> 09:57.606
You're serious.

09:57.767 --> 09:58.802
Yes, sir.

09:59.487 --> 10:00.886
I'm really glad we're here.

10:00.967 --> 10:03.117
That lady just walked into
a whole lot of help.

10:03.207 --> 10:04.959
Except for old Mr. Unipod, here.

10:05.047 --> 10:06.765
Speaking of walked into. Decker!

10:06.847 --> 10:08.644
[Police sirens wailing]

10:08.727 --> 10:09.921
[Tyres squealing]

10:10.007 --> 10:11.076
DECKER: There they are.

10:11.167 --> 10:13.123
HANNIBAL: We're joining
the medical profession.

10:13.207 --> 10:14.720
[Sirens blaring]

10:14.807 --> 10:16.399
[Tyres screeching]

10:19.807 --> 10:22.765
All right. I want a clean sweep.

10:23.167 --> 10:24.282
All of them.

10:24.487 --> 10:27.126
You two, around the back. Let's go, men.

10:39.447 --> 10:41.722
You two, take that hall. Go.

10:56.807 --> 10:57.876
Perfect.

11:01.247 --> 11:05.081
SURGEON: What the hell is this?
This is a sterile operating room! Out!

11:06.567 --> 11:07.795
Not here.

11:08.967 --> 11:11.959
Are you people insane?
We're supposed to operate here!

11:14.127 --> 11:17.278
Will someone kindly tell me
what this is all about?

11:17.367 --> 11:20.803
Give it to me straight, Doc.
Will I ever play the violin again?

11:21.967 --> 11:23.844
[Rapid, suspenseful drumbeat]

11:25.567 --> 11:27.797
Be careful, sucker.
This ain't no funny car race.

11:27.887 --> 11:29.684
MURDOCK: Leave the driving to us.

11:37.727 --> 11:39.445
[Drumbeat continues]

11:44.927 --> 11:47.157
[Fast-paced instrumental music]

11:47.807 --> 11:49.001
MAN: They're getting away!

11:49.087 --> 11:50.679
[Truck starting]

11:53.487 --> 11:55.762
[Adventurous instrumental music]

11:56.207 --> 11:58.004
[Police siren blaring]

12:09.487 --> 12:11.159
[Machine gun firing]

12:14.327 --> 12:16.283
[Tense instrumental music]

12:19.807 --> 12:21.798
Hannibal's on the serious jazz.

12:21.967 --> 12:25.721
Well, maybe we'll get lucky and one day
modern medicine will find a cure.

12:25.807 --> 12:27.957
[Cheerful instrumental music]

12:35.087 --> 12:37.078
[Murdock humming comically]

12:44.327 --> 12:46.363
Murdock, this looks crazy even for you.

12:46.447 --> 12:48.836
B.A., it's just animal vibe therapy.

12:48.927 --> 12:51.725
I do it all the time back at the V.A. to relax.

12:51.807 --> 12:54.526
Thermador here is helping me to cool out!

12:57.527 --> 12:59.518
AMY: Have you been doing this all your life?

12:59.607 --> 13:00.881
Yeah, we started helping Dad...

13:00.967 --> 13:03.845
as soon as we were old enough
to wrestle a lobster from a trap.

13:03.927 --> 13:05.246
HANNIBAL: How is your father?

13:05.327 --> 13:07.636
I don't know.
Shana's with him at a hospital in L.A.

13:07.727 --> 13:09.558
Said she'd call if she found out anything.

13:09.647 --> 13:12.161
I can't figure out why
some of the people around here...

13:12.247 --> 13:15.000
don't help you take
the bend out of Garber's hook a little.

13:15.087 --> 13:16.884
FACE: Stand up to him.
DOUG: They're scared.

13:16.967 --> 13:19.800
Anybody who's tried to fight him
got hurt bad and gave up.

13:19.887 --> 13:21.639
And those who went along with him...

13:21.727 --> 13:24.241
they stayed in business,
but they had to give him a cut.

13:24.327 --> 13:26.887
Half the profits. Pretty deep cut.

13:26.967 --> 13:28.082
DOUG: Yeah.

13:29.727 --> 13:31.399
How do you deal with a man like this?

13:31.487 --> 13:34.365
I mean, my father's in the hospital,
hanging on by a thread.

13:34.447 --> 13:36.438
I want to stop Garber...

13:36.527 --> 13:38.722
but I don't want to lose my family
in the process.

13:38.807 --> 13:40.604
We're sorry about your father.

13:40.687 --> 13:42.678
We can't do anything about that.

13:42.927 --> 13:44.599
But we can do the next best thing.

13:44.687 --> 13:46.086
And we'll do it to Garber.

13:46.167 --> 13:49.523
Thanks, but I couldn't ask you to do that.
It's too risky.

13:49.607 --> 13:52.758
You don't have to ask us.
Guys like Garber attract us.

13:52.847 --> 13:54.326
MURDOCK: Hannibal...

13:54.767 --> 13:58.123
little Thermador here wants to know
what are we gonna do?

13:58.207 --> 14:02.359
I think it's time for Mr. Garber to learn
a lesson in the survival of the toughest.

14:02.447 --> 14:05.405
B.A., what do the repairs
on this boat look like?

14:05.887 --> 14:09.163
It won't be easy, man.
I checked the engine. It looked pretty bad.

14:09.247 --> 14:11.886
Doug, is there a marine supply house
around here?

14:11.967 --> 14:15.960
Hagopian's Boat Yard's
half a mile down by the wharf.

14:16.887 --> 14:20.482
DOUG: But he won't sell us anything.
He's in Garber's back pocket.

14:20.607 --> 14:22.962
Pockets are made to be reached into.

14:23.247 --> 14:24.316
Let's go, gang.

14:37.727 --> 14:39.001
[Dog growling]

14:41.567 --> 14:42.841
[Snarling]

14:45.007 --> 14:46.326
[Dog barks]

14:48.687 --> 14:50.200
Cutter, shut up!

14:51.487 --> 14:54.524
It's all right, fellows.
It's gonna be no problem at all.

14:54.607 --> 14:57.041
I'm vibing even as I speak.

14:57.167 --> 14:58.839
[Barking continues]

15:00.927 --> 15:02.519
[Murdock hissing]

15:05.567 --> 15:08.206
Bad vibes. That's very bad vibes.

15:09.527 --> 15:12.166
Nice dog. What breed is he, piranha?

15:14.927 --> 15:17.043
Say, Mr. Hagopian...

15:17.807 --> 15:19.798
we need some fibreglass for a busted hull...

15:19.887 --> 15:23.846
resin, brushes, instruments, engine parts,
that's for an inboard, not an outboard...

15:23.927 --> 15:26.077
fuel tanks, fuel line. It's all on this list.

15:26.167 --> 15:28.362
Look, pal, this is a real small town.

15:28.447 --> 15:31.723
Only one boat around here
needs the kind of stuff you're talking about.

15:31.807 --> 15:35.004
And the fellow I work for says
that boat stays just the way it is.

15:35.087 --> 15:36.998
So it looks like I'm all out of everything.

15:37.087 --> 15:39.476
Hey, jack, I see the stuff we need
right over there.

15:39.567 --> 15:42.798
- And you're saying it's gone?
- I'm saying I sell to who I want to.

15:42.887 --> 15:46.675
Now, you better get off my property
before I turn Cutter loose on you.

15:47.327 --> 15:50.125
You should learn to use your anger
more constructively.

15:50.207 --> 15:51.356
You ever try meditating?

15:51.447 --> 15:54.245
Hey, Hannibal,
I think we ought to bust this guy's rudder.

15:54.327 --> 15:55.442
Easy, B.A.

15:55.527 --> 15:57.722
I'm sure Mr. Hagopian's just a little cranky...

15:57.807 --> 16:00.924
because he got tired
polishing all these nifty boats.

16:01.407 --> 16:04.797
I'm sure he'll give us just what we want
at the price we want.

16:06.127 --> 16:07.321
[Gun clicking]

16:07.407 --> 16:08.920
You're never gonna pull this off.

16:09.007 --> 16:11.999
I don't mean to be a know-it-all,
but we already have.

16:12.807 --> 16:13.956
Fill it!

16:14.207 --> 16:16.243
I'll go see what I got back here.

16:17.887 --> 16:20.720
You know, of course,
he'll go inside and call Garber.

16:20.807 --> 16:22.035
I certainly hope so.

16:22.127 --> 16:26.439
I hate to go looking for a sleaze like that
when we can have him delivered to us.

16:30.927 --> 16:32.565
[Cars approaching]

16:34.207 --> 16:35.799
[Tyres screeching]

16:35.967 --> 16:37.878
Anybody we know, Thermy?

16:50.727 --> 16:53.195
You wouldn't be a suckfish named Garber,
would you?

16:53.287 --> 16:56.085
Now, what would you boys be wanting
with all this equipment?

16:56.167 --> 16:59.716
There's a message in that for you.
Your little protection racket is over.

16:59.807 --> 17:02.275
And if you lean on the Mayers once more...

17:02.687 --> 17:05.326
you're gonna be shopping
for some new kneecaps.

17:05.567 --> 17:08.035
Face, read this guy what he owes up to date.

17:08.127 --> 17:09.242
My pleasure.

17:10.367 --> 17:14.679
For extorted profits from fishermen,
damaged properties, and for duress...

17:15.087 --> 17:18.318
we figure you owe
the people of Lobster Bay $300,000.

17:18.607 --> 17:21.963
That's a tentative figure, of course.
Probably a lot larger.

17:22.207 --> 17:23.606
You people are real funny.

17:23.686 --> 17:26.201
We supposed to be scared of you guys?

17:29.087 --> 17:30.202
That's up to you.

17:30.287 --> 17:33.085
We'd like it if you and your sisters
would grow some brains...

17:33.167 --> 17:34.316
and get out of town.

17:34.407 --> 17:35.442
For good.

17:35.527 --> 17:37.836
I suppose you want your answer now.

17:41.927 --> 17:43.246
Well, you got it.

17:44.727 --> 17:46.683
[Tense instrumental music]

17:48.767 --> 17:49.961
[Grunts]

17:57.047 --> 17:59.197
You're gonna be sorry you did that!

18:04.807 --> 18:05.876
[Screaming]

18:05.967 --> 18:07.002
[Groaning]

18:07.087 --> 18:08.725
B.A.: Murdock, you fool!

18:20.647 --> 18:21.841
[Groans]

18:29.487 --> 18:31.318
You've been warned, Garber.

18:32.447 --> 18:33.516
Let's go.

18:33.767 --> 18:35.598
Look what they did to Thermy, Hannibal.

18:35.687 --> 18:38.326
- Maybe I could put some water on him and...
- No.

18:38.567 --> 18:40.717
But his spirit lives, Captain.

18:51.327 --> 18:53.397
Thermy will get another chance, Murdock.

18:53.487 --> 18:56.285
Garber isn't half done, if I read him right.

18:57.887 --> 18:59.957
[Dramatic instrumental music]

19:15.807 --> 19:16.842
Yeah?

19:16.927 --> 19:18.918
DECKER: Miss Mayer?
SHANA: Yes.

19:19.167 --> 19:21.601
DECKER: I'm Col. Decker, Military Police.

19:21.927 --> 19:23.883
This is Capt. Crane.

19:24.127 --> 19:26.118
Howdy. You guys recruiting?

19:26.767 --> 19:28.883
Sorry to trouble you,
but we have information...

19:28.967 --> 19:31.527
that you were seen
at the emergency hospital yesterday...

19:31.607 --> 19:33.802
talking to people
that Col. Decker's looking for.

19:33.887 --> 19:36.959
They're escaped military prisoners.
Extremely dangerous.

19:37.327 --> 19:39.602
Who? Those folks just passing through?

19:40.207 --> 19:41.720
We barely spoke.

19:41.887 --> 19:45.800
And if you're asking if I know
where they might be, I have no idea.

19:46.047 --> 19:48.197
Ma'am, I'm not calling you a liar...

19:48.647 --> 19:51.957
but regulations require
that we check the premises of any person...

19:52.047 --> 19:54.686
who's reported to have been seen
with these individuals.

19:54.767 --> 19:57.440
How do we know they're not holding
a gun on you right now?

19:57.527 --> 19:58.926
You got a search warrant?

19:59.007 --> 20:03.205
Son, when you can get a warrant
as quick as I can, you don't need one.

20:03.367 --> 20:05.085
Now, you want to step aside?

20:05.167 --> 20:07.203
This'll only take a minute.

20:16.647 --> 20:18.603
[Slow instrumental music]

20:31.367 --> 20:34.040
[Lightly suspenseful instrumental music]

20:38.367 --> 20:40.801
One van, well hidden, hold the mayo.

20:44.487 --> 20:46.079
[Doorbell ringing]

20:48.127 --> 20:50.322
[Suspenseful music intensifies]

20:53.567 --> 20:55.956
SHANA: The Army was here looking for you.

20:56.047 --> 20:57.878
Don't tell me Col. Decker came by here?

20:57.967 --> 21:00.401
You didn't say the Army was after you.
What did you do?

21:00.487 --> 21:01.636
That's a long story.

21:01.727 --> 21:03.080
B.A., you better keep a lookout.

21:03.167 --> 21:06.284
All I can say is we're right, they're wrong
and hope you believe us.

21:06.367 --> 21:09.484
They forced their way inside,
checked the house from top to bottom.

21:09.567 --> 21:11.046
They're awful anxious to get you.

21:11.127 --> 21:12.924
AMY: Getting a little cosy.
HANNIBAL: Yeah.

21:13.007 --> 21:15.646
We'll speed it up.
Take care of Garber and get out of town.

21:15.727 --> 21:17.206
DOUG: Don't know how you can do that.

21:17.287 --> 21:20.006
Garber has so many of the local fishermen
under his thumb...

21:20.087 --> 21:22.362
that they're out 24 hours a day
depleting the beds.

21:22.447 --> 21:25.405
Maybe it's just not realistic
that you can take care of Garber...

21:25.487 --> 21:27.955
and get away from this Col. Decker
at the same time.

21:28.047 --> 21:29.082
We enjoy a challenge.

21:29.167 --> 21:31.681
We need a couple of hours.
We'll have this onion peeled.

21:31.767 --> 21:32.802
HANNIBAL: Let's get going.

21:32.887 --> 21:35.640
In the meantime, Face,
you might renew your acquaintance...

21:35.727 --> 21:38.287
with your old friend, Magnificent Templeton.

21:49.087 --> 21:50.805
[Humming cheerfully]

21:55.087 --> 21:56.759
[Face clears throat]

21:58.047 --> 21:59.082
Hi.

21:59.207 --> 22:00.799
[Speaking French]

22:01.887 --> 22:03.366
Allow me to introduce myself.

22:03.447 --> 22:07.679
[French accent] I am The Magnificent
Templeton. Prestidigitator extraordinaire.

22:07.927 --> 22:09.565
- Magnificent Templeton?
- Oui.

22:09.647 --> 22:10.716
A magician?

22:10.807 --> 22:15.039
I prefer to think of myself more
as a man possessed of the fantastic powers.

22:15.127 --> 22:18.722
You have perhaps seen me
on the American TV program, Merv Griffin?

22:19.647 --> 22:20.682
No?

22:21.567 --> 22:25.560
A sense of humour. I like this. VoilÃ .

22:27.727 --> 22:29.080
Wowee!

22:29.167 --> 22:31.044
BETTY: That is...
FACE: Yeah.

22:33.247 --> 22:35.124
Maybe I have seen you on TV.

22:35.207 --> 22:38.119
But of course. Now, to business.

22:38.207 --> 22:40.118
You are Freddy, oui?

22:40.367 --> 22:43.803
No. Freddy's is up the street.
But he's on vacation.

22:44.327 --> 22:47.285
Anyway, that's Freddy's Scuba.
This is Betty's Scuba.

22:47.847 --> 22:48.916
Wrong shop.

22:49.527 --> 22:53.520
Betty, Freddy.
It's a very similar sound, is it not?

22:53.607 --> 22:56.917
Betty, Freddy, Freddy, Betty, Betty, Freddy.

22:57.007 --> 22:58.360
What kind of an accent is that?

22:58.447 --> 23:01.166
Because I've never exactly heard one
just like that before.

23:01.247 --> 23:02.885
Where are you from?

23:03.327 --> 23:06.478
I'll bet you're from Switzerland
or somewhere like that, right?

23:06.567 --> 23:08.603
Not Switzerland.

23:10.007 --> 23:12.760
[Without French accent]
Look, you seem like a nice girl, Betty.

23:12.847 --> 23:15.315
I can't just stand here
and lie to you like this.

23:15.407 --> 23:19.002
Fact is, I only do the accent
to make my manager happy.

23:19.567 --> 23:23.003
You know, he swears
that if I don't do the accent all the time...

23:23.087 --> 23:25.806
The Magnificent Templeton
will lose credibility, see.

23:25.887 --> 23:29.243
Well, it's amazing the way you do it.
I was fooled. Really!

23:29.767 --> 23:32.759
Well, Betty, it's all part
of the game of magic.

23:33.887 --> 23:36.447
Fantasy is my middle name.

23:37.407 --> 23:40.046
Anyway, getting back to magic.

23:40.527 --> 23:44.076
If Freddy is out of town,
I definitely have a problem.

23:45.407 --> 23:46.999
Is there anything I could do?

23:47.087 --> 23:49.123
No. I don't want to trouble you.

23:49.207 --> 23:52.882
You see, it's just that I've got to do
this benefit show up north...

23:53.087 --> 23:55.965
I was robbed this morning at my motel,
at gunpoint.

23:56.087 --> 23:58.555
- They even took my air tanks.
- Air tanks?

23:59.047 --> 24:01.686
That's for the Tank of Doom illusion.

24:01.847 --> 24:04.680
- Tank of Doom?
- It's unbelievable.

24:04.767 --> 24:09.204
I've got this large water tank that's divided
into two chambers by a glass partition.

24:09.287 --> 24:12.165
Now, on one side, all bound up and tied...

24:12.247 --> 24:13.885
- You?
- Moi.

24:13.967 --> 24:16.276
And on the other side is a shark.

24:16.367 --> 24:18.198
- A great white.
- You got it.

24:18.327 --> 24:20.966
There's an hourglass timer full of sand, see.

24:21.087 --> 24:24.921
And when the sand runs out,
that releases a lever that raises the partition.

24:25.007 --> 24:27.840
- What if you're not out of there?
- Jaws 4.

24:28.607 --> 24:31.644
No, but without the air tanks, see,
I can't even attempt it.

24:31.727 --> 24:33.877
And now that Freddy's out of town...

24:33.967 --> 24:36.083
He'll be gone for a month, at least.

24:38.007 --> 24:40.965
- When did you need the tanks?
- Tonight.

24:41.367 --> 24:42.766
It's for a TV special.

24:42.847 --> 24:45.600
It's being picked up by satellite,
shown all over the world.

24:45.687 --> 24:47.359
All the networks are bidding for it.

24:47.447 --> 24:50.484
It's gonna be shown in London, France,
Paris, Uruguay...

24:50.567 --> 24:54.242
Well, you have to have air tanks.

24:55.247 --> 24:56.600
Betty, no, no.

24:56.687 --> 24:59.645
You're suggesting that you loan me...
No, no.

24:59.727 --> 25:02.321
- We hardly know each other.
- Well...

25:02.687 --> 25:06.043
Sure. I mean,
I don't want to see you get eaten up.

25:06.167 --> 25:08.397
Betty, you are wonderful.

25:08.487 --> 25:10.523
The whole thing will be
in the can by tonight.

25:10.607 --> 25:11.960
I'll bring the stuff back...

25:12.047 --> 25:15.483
and you and I will go out
and find ourselves a little maison...

25:15.807 --> 25:18.480
let the wine flow, the candles flicker.

25:18.687 --> 25:20.917
I'll start filling the tanks.

25:22.287 --> 25:25.245
Boy, I sure am glad I met you.

25:25.767 --> 25:26.802
Me, too.

25:35.487 --> 25:36.920
FACE: Oh, come on.

25:47.847 --> 25:48.836
Hi, there.

25:48.927 --> 25:52.522
Boy, is it stuffy in here.
By the way, these are very good.

25:52.847 --> 25:57.238
I loved the Danish, but you know,
they could use just a pinch more cinnamon.

26:05.327 --> 26:07.045
FACE: All right, Hannibal.

26:07.167 --> 26:11.319
[French accent] Here's your aquaman
costume, right down to the flippers.

26:12.127 --> 26:13.879
Now, what do you expect to do with it?

26:13.967 --> 26:15.082
What do you mean, me?

26:15.167 --> 26:18.364
Come on, I got the stuff.
Let somebody else get wet in it.

26:19.007 --> 26:21.680
It's time for you and Murdock
to explore the murky depths.

26:21.767 --> 26:23.883
Hannibal, you know I have a sinus problem.

26:23.967 --> 26:27.277
I go down there, I'm clog-city for weeks.
I'll sound like a bus.

26:27.367 --> 26:31.326
Come on, Face. We could have lots of fun.
I mean, fish are tons of fun.

26:31.407 --> 26:34.922
Lots of them have a great sense of humour.
Some watch TV and everything.

26:35.007 --> 26:37.077
The two of you could really have a ball.

26:37.167 --> 26:39.601
AMY: I didn't know you were a diver, Face.
FACE: I'm not.

26:39.687 --> 26:43.157
Hannibal and B.A. are the guys
with the experience below the water line...

26:43.247 --> 26:45.715
mining bridges in Nam.
Hannibal, why don't you do it?

26:45.807 --> 26:47.638
You know he's got a point there, Hannibal.

26:47.727 --> 26:50.799
B.A.'s got an excuse because of his foot,
but what about you?

26:50.887 --> 26:54.357
Well, it's simple. I'm the planner.
I plan better in dry air.

26:55.007 --> 26:57.475
Besides, B.A. and I have been working out.

26:57.567 --> 26:59.080
You two look a little flabby.

26:59.167 --> 27:02.477
Flabby? Just exactly what are we supposed
to do down there, Hannibal...

27:02.567 --> 27:04.319
other than not drink the water?

27:04.407 --> 27:07.524
Make it hot for Garber.
Come on, we got work to do.

27:07.607 --> 27:08.881
[B.A. grunting]

27:10.327 --> 27:12.557
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

27:12.727 --> 27:14.001
[Clicking]

27:27.807 --> 27:29.081
[Hissing]

27:35.807 --> 27:38.640
[Suspenseful instrumental music intensifies]

28:21.527 --> 28:22.721
[Coughs]

28:23.247 --> 28:24.760
FACE: Give me a hand.
HANNIBAL: Okay.

28:24.847 --> 28:26.121
[Grunting]

28:27.727 --> 28:29.638
B.A.: Watch out for that hose.

28:36.607 --> 28:37.881
[Grunting]

28:40.927 --> 28:44.556
All things considered,
I'd like to do this in the Bahamas next time.

28:45.287 --> 28:48.085
You know, Hannibal,
going back down there again...

28:48.167 --> 28:51.079
I almost had the feeling
that Therm was there with me.

28:51.167 --> 28:53.522
He is, fool. You got the claw in your pocket.

28:53.607 --> 28:55.484
Now, did you get the charges set?

28:55.567 --> 28:56.966
Ready to go boom.

29:00.287 --> 29:01.322
Do it.

29:01.887 --> 29:04.355
Okay, yank them. Man wants to get in quick.

29:04.447 --> 29:05.880
[Rope creaking]

29:07.167 --> 29:08.486
[Squeaking]

29:09.487 --> 29:12.923
Hannibal, may I? For the Therm?

29:25.327 --> 29:26.362
[Murdock chuckling]

29:26.447 --> 29:28.677
HANNIBAL: Let's get to the boat, B.A.

29:28.807 --> 29:30.479
What's going on out here?

29:31.207 --> 29:33.482
Someone's been messing with our traps.

29:33.967 --> 29:36.083
Found a bottle in that one over there.

29:36.167 --> 29:37.520
That's cute.

29:37.607 --> 29:39.165
[Glass shattering]

29:41.327 --> 29:44.125
"Lobster are red, water is blue.

29:44.207 --> 29:46.721
"Put up your hands and look behind you. "

29:46.887 --> 29:49.162
GARBER: Right.
HANNIBAL: Up in the air!

29:50.767 --> 29:53.235
We're gonna balance some scales
around here, Garber.

29:53.327 --> 29:54.965
You know what piracy is, mister?

29:55.047 --> 29:59.120
Yeah. I know what extortion
and a protection racket is, too, pal.

29:59.207 --> 30:01.004
We're just here to make a little point.

30:01.087 --> 30:04.204
We want you to know what it feels like
to get your toes stepped on.

30:04.287 --> 30:06.482
When we were down there
setting the explosives...

30:06.567 --> 30:10.037
we took some pictures of the undersized,
illegal lobsters you catch.

30:10.127 --> 30:12.766
A friend of ours writes
for a syndicate of 80 newspapers.

30:12.847 --> 30:14.758
She'll love a story like this.

30:14.847 --> 30:17.998
I figure in a couple of days
the whole country will know about you.

30:18.087 --> 30:20.317
- Well, you ain't gonna get away with this.
- Funny.

30:20.407 --> 30:22.079
Every time somebody says that to me...

30:22.167 --> 30:24.203
they wind up eating those words
on sourdough.

30:24.287 --> 30:26.164
DECKER: Not this time, Smith!

30:27.167 --> 30:28.395
Check the boat.

30:28.567 --> 30:30.797
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

30:35.007 --> 30:36.486
Nobody's in the boat.

30:36.767 --> 30:38.678
Nobody's in the boat, sir.

30:39.527 --> 30:41.085
You gotta watch that guy, Decker.

30:41.167 --> 30:43.044
Tie them up and shut them up!

30:46.367 --> 30:48.403
[Heroic instrumental music]

30:58.367 --> 31:00.483
[Dramatic instrumental music]

31:11.047 --> 31:13.197
DECKER: All right, let's go. Move it!

31:13.287 --> 31:14.686
Head for that shed.

31:15.767 --> 31:18.759
Well, you really know
how to do things right, Colonel.

31:19.007 --> 31:21.362
A baby-blue shed. What do you say, Face?

31:21.447 --> 31:23.324
Yeah, West Point, all the way.

31:23.487 --> 31:25.239
Nothing's too good for you.

31:25.327 --> 31:28.478
And don't worry.
I've sent for military transport.

31:28.727 --> 31:30.365
It'll be here in an hour.

31:31.207 --> 31:35.325
By tomorrow morning you'll be eating
breakfast with 500 guys just like you.

31:35.407 --> 31:37.557
There is nobody just like us.

31:37.647 --> 31:40.002
You really think you're gonna put us away,
don't you?

31:40.087 --> 31:41.486
Yeah, and I back up what I think.

31:41.567 --> 31:43.797
I hope you haven't got
any money bet on that, pal.

31:43.887 --> 31:45.923
Hope you enjoy
your little stay in the slammer.

31:46.007 --> 31:47.156
DECKER: Cut it, Garber!

31:47.247 --> 31:48.726
If you hadn't cooperated with me...

31:48.807 --> 31:51.765
I'd turn you over to the police, the FBl,
anybody who'd have you.

31:51.847 --> 31:54.520
We sure get holy
after we get what we want, don't we?

31:54.607 --> 31:56.245
I never do agree with Col. Smith...

31:56.327 --> 32:00.206
but your little protection scam cuts about
as much ice with me as it does with him.

32:00.287 --> 32:04.599
Now pull up your last load of traps
and get out of this town before I run you in.

32:06.167 --> 32:08.965
Garber hates Decker, Decker hates Garber.
Perfect.

32:09.407 --> 32:10.965
Well, you just listen to this.

32:11.047 --> 32:14.244
I get washed out of this thing,
I ain't going alone.

32:14.327 --> 32:16.921
I'll take a big chunk of your friends with me.

32:17.007 --> 32:18.042
Bet on it.

32:18.247 --> 32:19.646
CRANE: Go on, inside.

32:19.727 --> 32:21.240
[B.A. screams in pain]

32:21.327 --> 32:23.636
Watch it, sucker! I got a bad foot.

32:23.727 --> 32:27.242
You shove me again
and I'll wrap that gun around your face.

32:27.807 --> 32:30.367
[Slow, suspenseful instrumental music]

32:44.767 --> 32:48.316
Hey, Hannibal, if you ever had a plan,
we're gonna need one now.

32:48.447 --> 32:50.039
The truck gets here within an hour.

32:50.127 --> 32:52.925
I've got a plan,
but it's for Garber and Decker.

32:53.927 --> 32:55.724
I'm not worried about us...

32:55.807 --> 32:58.196
but Garber would kill Doug and Shana
in a minute.

32:58.287 --> 32:59.481
Nobody's gonna kill us.

32:59.567 --> 33:01.637
Well, there's nothing we can do
about it now.

33:01.727 --> 33:03.319
- Unless...
- Unless?

33:03.567 --> 33:04.920
You mean Murdock?

33:05.807 --> 33:09.117
Well, I guess what they say is true.
America is running out of heroes.

33:09.207 --> 33:11.118
Murdock will pop up somewhere.

33:16.127 --> 33:17.162
Amy!

33:20.047 --> 33:21.560
AMY: Murdock, what happened?

33:21.647 --> 33:24.320
We're in big trouble. Big trouble.

33:25.127 --> 33:27.038
The unit was captured by Decker.

33:27.127 --> 33:29.197
There was an ambush on Garber's boat.

33:29.287 --> 33:30.481
So what're we gonna do?

33:30.567 --> 33:33.127
Don't worry. I thought about something
while swimming in.

33:33.207 --> 33:34.686
The water sort of clears the brain.

33:34.767 --> 33:36.280
Is there anything we can do to help?

33:36.367 --> 33:38.597
I don't want you getting in trouble over us.

33:38.687 --> 33:40.757
MURDOCK: It's getting bigger.
AMY: What's your idea?

33:40.847 --> 33:42.997
I figure that Decker is a creature of habit.

33:43.087 --> 33:46.966
And he would never come down after us
with heavy wheels weighing him down.

33:47.047 --> 33:49.402
So he's gonna have to reach out
and grab Uncle Sam...

33:49.487 --> 33:50.920
and get a transport down here.

33:51.007 --> 33:55.046
The closest base from here is Fort Newton.
That's about 100 miles north.

33:55.287 --> 33:56.606
Okay.

33:56.727 --> 34:01.039
That means he's gonna have to head down
the highway south, straight through town.

34:01.727 --> 34:02.762
Amy...

34:04.007 --> 34:07.841
I'm gonna make you feel real wanted.
You know what I mean?

34:08.487 --> 34:10.318
Real wanted.

34:21.687 --> 34:23.279
[Tyres screeching]

34:27.167 --> 34:28.646
Hold it, mister!

34:29.167 --> 34:31.362
Mind your own business, doughboy!

34:31.647 --> 34:34.719
We're breaking up and she won't give me
my letterman jacket back.

34:34.806 --> 34:36.956
Why don't you lose that cap pistol
and take a lap?

34:37.047 --> 34:39.641
Yeah. You leave my boyfriend alone.

34:40.087 --> 34:41.235
[Gun clicks]

34:41.327 --> 34:43.887
I knew you couldn't take it
without me, baby.

34:44.286 --> 34:45.481
Turn around.

34:45.887 --> 34:46.922
March.

34:55.927 --> 34:57.246
All ready to go, Mr. Garber.

34:57.327 --> 34:59.363
We shove out of town anytime you want.

34:59.447 --> 35:01.677
We ain't leaving town yet, Lennox.

35:02.207 --> 35:04.960
I want to pay my respects to the Mayers.

35:06.767 --> 35:09.281
You know, we've been here almost an hour.

35:09.727 --> 35:12.082
Don't tell me what time it is!

35:12.167 --> 35:14.476
Tell me what a great plan
you just thought of.

35:14.567 --> 35:17.365
You still think Amy and Murdock
are gonna get us out of here?

35:17.447 --> 35:20.245
- Bet on it.
- Yeah. I got no choice.

35:20.527 --> 35:22.597
[Military truck approaching]

35:27.967 --> 35:29.036
Here it comes.

35:29.127 --> 35:32.164
Get them out, Captain,
and keep them under heavy guard.

35:42.687 --> 35:44.518
Incidentally, I did a little figuring.

35:44.607 --> 35:47.838
Our odds are about 20-to-1, give or take.
Thought you'd like to know.

35:47.927 --> 35:49.963
- Thanks, Murdock.
- You better put it on.

35:50.047 --> 35:52.436
This bag of chips could get pretty hairy.
Okay?

35:52.527 --> 35:54.438
Two, three, one.

35:55.847 --> 35:56.916
FACE: Uh-oh.

35:57.007 --> 35:59.885
- Still think we're gonna get rescued?
- Why not?

36:08.967 --> 36:12.437
MURDOCK: I want to hear the guns
hit the deck, gentlemen.

36:14.247 --> 36:16.317
You're gritting your teeth, Decker.

36:16.967 --> 36:18.639
FACE: Go on, inside! Move!

36:25.887 --> 36:27.923
You're wasting the best years of your life...

36:28.007 --> 36:30.726
trying to catch people
you're never gonna catch.

36:30.927 --> 36:32.599
Let me give you some advice.

36:32.687 --> 36:35.963
Go back to your hometown.
Open up an Army-Navy store.

36:36.087 --> 36:37.406
You're a born clerk.

36:37.487 --> 36:38.522
B.A.

36:38.847 --> 36:39.996
All right. Let's go.

36:40.087 --> 36:42.999
Garber's leaving town,
but he'll go after Doug and Shana first.

36:43.087 --> 36:44.361
AMY: They're on their boat.

36:44.567 --> 36:46.762
HANNIBAL: Then that's where it'll happen.

36:46.847 --> 36:49.077
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

36:55.007 --> 36:56.156
What's this?

36:56.287 --> 36:58.403
[Dramatic instrumental music]

37:33.527 --> 37:35.643
Your family's caused me
an awful lot of trouble.

37:35.727 --> 37:37.479
Enough to kill us over?

37:38.727 --> 37:40.046
How's your daddy?

37:40.807 --> 37:41.956
Break it up!

37:46.207 --> 37:48.277
First we're gonna bust up the boat.

37:48.727 --> 37:50.206
Then we're gonna take care of you.

37:50.287 --> 37:52.721
- You've lost, Garber.
- Yeah?

37:52.807 --> 37:55.685
- Where did you hear that fairy tale at?
- From me.

37:57.047 --> 37:59.561
[Slow, suspenseful instrumental music]

38:02.007 --> 38:04.282
It's called
The Three Little Pigs Named Garber.

38:04.367 --> 38:06.835
I thought you'd enjoy the same surprise
you had for us.

38:06.927 --> 38:09.202
Yeah. One good turn deserves another.

38:32.287 --> 38:34.755
HANNIBAL: Face, I'm out of ammo. Cover me.

38:35.207 --> 38:37.163
[Tense instrumental music]

38:38.087 --> 38:39.281
[Grunts]

38:42.447 --> 38:45.519
MURDOCK: Hold it right there, Popeye.
Dropamente.

38:53.567 --> 38:54.716
[Grunts]

39:03.167 --> 39:05.078
[Tense instrumental music]

39:07.647 --> 39:09.126
[Drum crashing]

39:09.887 --> 39:11.036
B.A.: Come on!

39:13.247 --> 39:14.726
[Loud grunting]

39:16.967 --> 39:18.286
[Screaming]

39:24.287 --> 39:26.039
That's for my foot, sucker!

39:52.047 --> 39:53.275
[Panting]

39:53.727 --> 39:54.955
[Screams]

39:56.927 --> 39:59.157
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

40:05.887 --> 40:07.445
HANNIBAL: You've got two choices.

40:07.527 --> 40:10.360
Either you get out of town
and never come back...

40:10.447 --> 40:14.520
or we'll tow you so far out to sea,
the next thing you'll see is Australia.

40:14.807 --> 40:19.403
You know what'll happen then?
Your mail will start stacking up, forever.

40:19.647 --> 40:21.797
You guys don't have any authority over me.

40:21.887 --> 40:24.685
I know you're a bunch of criminals
on the run from the Army.

40:24.767 --> 40:26.280
You can't threaten me.

40:28.007 --> 40:29.565
What do you call this?

40:29.647 --> 40:31.319
It's okay, B.A.

40:31.407 --> 40:33.443
I kind of hoped he'd say that.

40:34.487 --> 40:37.843
Here, Doug, keep that on him...

40:37.927 --> 40:40.122
till Decker gets here.

40:40.207 --> 40:42.641
Of course, we'll have to duck out
so as to miss him...

40:42.727 --> 40:45.002
but he'll be thrilled to see
you haven't left town.

40:45.087 --> 40:48.796
He gets his jollies sticking people
in boxes the size of coffee cups.

40:48.887 --> 40:50.798
You ought to fit just fine.

40:50.887 --> 40:54.243
HANNIBAL: We tend to frustrate him.
He'll take it out on you.

40:55.167 --> 40:58.637
Decker finally catches somebody: Garber.

41:00.207 --> 41:02.846
I love it when a plan comes together.

41:10.127 --> 41:12.436
DOUG: You should have seen the look
on Garber's face...

41:12.527 --> 41:14.916
when the Army showed up
and hauled him off.

41:15.007 --> 41:19.000
I'd like to see the look on Decker's face.
He didn't catch what he was fishing for.

41:19.087 --> 41:21.123
SHANA: We're real glad about that, too.

41:21.207 --> 41:24.438
You guys have been real good to us,
criminals or not.

41:24.887 --> 41:27.765
B.A.: I'm glad your father's all right.
SHANA: Are you kidding?

41:27.847 --> 41:29.883
When I called to tell him
Garber was through...

41:29.967 --> 41:31.923
he started making plans to jog home.

41:32.007 --> 41:34.043
Sounds like a man on the road to health.

41:34.127 --> 41:37.039
Yeah, he's just sorry he didn't get a chance
to meet you all.

41:37.127 --> 41:39.641
Well, you never know.
We do travel a great deal.

41:39.727 --> 41:41.206
I don't know about you guys...

41:41.287 --> 41:44.165
but I was thinking of swimming
right on up the coast someday...

41:44.247 --> 41:46.522
and then surfing right on in and saying hey.

41:46.607 --> 41:48.245
Shut up, fool. You ain't no fish.

41:48.327 --> 41:50.761
Oh, yeah? I can pucker up like one.

41:50.847 --> 41:52.485
Besides, I like them fish vibes.

41:52.567 --> 41:55.525
I tell you, they got something
real peaceful going on down there.

41:55.607 --> 41:56.801
Right, Therm, my man?

41:56.887 --> 42:00.516
Listen, Murdock, I'm sick and tired
of your dead lobster and your dumb vibes.

42:00.607 --> 42:01.642
MURDOCK: Cut it out, B.A.

42:01.727 --> 42:05.515
Just because Therm has been reduced
to a claw, don't mean he ain't got no vibes.

42:05.607 --> 42:07.996
He's just keeping them on low beam...

42:08.087 --> 42:11.602
so he don't end up in a bisque somewhere...

42:11.687 --> 42:13.564
in some sleazy restaurant.

42:13.647 --> 42:14.762
You don't hear no vibes.

42:14.847 --> 42:17.805
You hear nothing but your pea brain
rolling around in your head.

42:17.887 --> 42:19.400
FACE: Come on, give the man a break.

42:19.487 --> 42:21.796
Not this time.
Gotta teach this sucker a lesson.

42:21.887 --> 42:25.516
Now, B.A., let's be rational.
We must behave like grown men.

42:25.607 --> 42:27.484
MURDOCK: Like civilised adults.

42:27.567 --> 42:31.196
The man said, "Give the man a break,"
so give me a break!

42:31.287 --> 42:32.925
How about I give you a ride?

42:33.007 --> 42:36.238
You want to be like the fish so much,
why don't you join them?

42:36.327 --> 42:38.363
[Comical instrumental music]

42:41.887 --> 42:44.606
He did it! I don't believe he did it!

42:45.407 --> 42:49.195
- Now, vibe on that, sucker!
- Vibe on that?

42:56.767 --> 42:58.166
[Theme music]

